Privacy Policy
Opt out or contact us anytime




The lawyer, Paul Schoeman, added: “Mr. Walters has a long history of investing in stocks that Mr. Icahn has publicly announced he’s interested in.”Mr. Mickelson was also mentioned during the trial as someone who had traded in Dean Foods shares and once owed nearly $2 million in gambling debts to Mr. Walters.Mr. Mickelson made roughly $1 million trading Dean Foods shares; he agreed to forfeit those profits in a related civil case brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission.Known as “Lefty” for his left-handed stroke, Mr. Mickelson was not criminally charged. Though he was once seen as a potential witness at Mr. Walters’s trial, he was never called to testify.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Prosecutors said that Mr. Walters had tried to hide his actions by supplying Mr. Davis with a prepaid cellphone called the Bat Phone to use while conveying secret information and by sometimes speaking in code.During the trial, prosecutors displayed phone logs and trading records, and an agent with the Federal Bureau of Investigation testified that Mr. Walters sometimes made major trades within moments of speaking with Mr. Davis on the phone.For instance, the agent testified, Mr. Davis and Mr. Walters spoke on the phone for 10 minutes one day in 2008 beginning at 12:54 p.m. At 1:05 p.m., Mr. Walters bought 462,200 shares of Dean Foods stock for about $9.3 million.Mr. Davis provided Mr. Walters with secret Dean Food information about future earnings statements, the planned purchase of another company and a pending initial public offering, prosecutors said.At the same time, Mr. Walters arranged for loans of nearly $1 million to Mr. Davis, who had financial problems and repaid only a small portion of what he borrowed, prosecutors said.Defense lawyers offered a contrasting account. They said that Mr. Walters was a skilled and fearless trader, referred to by one of his brokers as “the Babe Ruth of Risk,” who did not need inside information. Mr. Davis, Mr. Walters’s lawyers said, was trying to save himself by maligning Mr. Walters.The competing narratives were on display throughout the trial. Mr. Davis testified that he had acted as a “virtual conduit” of secrets and had supplied Mr. Walters with an “enormous” amount of information.At one point, Mr. Davis said, Mr. Walters provided him with the Bat Phone to use while communicating about Dean Foods, adding that later he had thrown it into a creek after federal agents visited his home.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Davis also testified that Mr. Walters sometimes spoke in code, using “Dallas Cowboys” to refer to Dean Foods and asking “How’s the milkman doing?” when inquiring about the company, then the country’s largest dairy processor.Defense lawyers cross-examined Mr. Davis at length, eliciting acknowledgments that he had been squeezed for money, had taken $100,000 from a charity he ran, had mislabeled expenses on his taxes and had lied to many people, including investigators with the S.E.C.Mr. Walters’s lawyers suggested that Mr. Davis had misled prosecutors about his sports gambling habits and his contact with prostitutes, at one point reading into the record phone numbers for escort services in Chicago, Denver, New York and San Francisco that Mr. Davis, who told prosecutors he had not hired prostitutes in recent years, had called in 2010, 2011 and 2014.Mr. Berke also questioned the existence of what he called the “so-called Bat Phone,” which was never recovered, pointing out that Mr. Davis had first told prosecutors that it was black before then testifying at trial that it was maroon.
Continue reading the main story






